# KSV-0118: linuxserver images set the runtime user via PUID/PGID env vars processed
# by s6-overlay, not via securityContext.runAsNonRoot. Adding runAsNonRoot: false
# would be misleading documentation; setting it true breaks PUID/PGID entirely.
KSV-0118

# DS-0002: linuxserver images must start as root so s6-overlay can write to
# /etc/passwd and /etc/group to apply PUID/PGID. Running as non-root disables
# PUID/PGID entirely, breaking NFS UID 1001 access.
DS-0002

# KSV-0014: linuxserver read-only mode disables PUID/PGID (falls back to UID 911),
# breaking NFS filesystem access. All workloads use linuxserver or similar images
# that legitimately write to their root filesystems for runtime state.
KSV-0014

# KSV-0009, KSV-0017: nodelocaldns requires hostNetwork to bind to the node loopback
# for DNS interception, and privileged to manage iptables rules. This is the only
# supported deployment method for node-local DNS caching.
KSV-0009
KSV-0017

# KSV-0041, KSV-0056, KSV-0114: cert-manager legitimately needs to read/write
# Secrets (that's how it stores TLS certificates) and manage webhook configurations.
# These come from the upstream vendor installer; the permissions are intentional.
KSV-0041
KSV-0056
KSV-0114

# KSV-0119: kube-vip's control-plane DaemonSet needs NET_RAW to emit the gratuitous
# ARP that claims the floating VIP on the node's L2 segment. NET_ADMIN+NET_RAW with
# hostNetwork is the upstream-prescribed ARP mode (cluster/kube-vip/kube-vip.yaml);
# dropping NET_RAW breaks the VIP. Same accepted-tradeoff class as nodelocaldns.
KSV-0119
